Thanks a lot for working on this, it looks very good! I left a few comments inline. 

Another more general comment: I like the result including a blend with uncorrected data using the `DayNightCompositor` (although a bit too blue), but in principle, the method `pyspectral.rayleigh.Rayleigh.reduce_rayleigh_highzenith` is doing the same thing as this blend with uncorrected. The only, yet significant, difference is that the `DayNightCompositor` does the scaling across the blending area in `cos(sunz)`-space, whereas in this PR the scaling is in `sunz`-space. Could you try and see what happens if you convert the `sunz`, `lim_low` and `lim_high` to cosine-space before sending them them to `reduce_rayleigh_highzenith`?

@simonrp84 what did you actually have in mind for the implementation in pyspectral? To do the scaling with `sunz` or `cos(sunz)`?

In the future we might want to introduce `@loadable_source_asset`:

```python
@loadable_source_asset
def my_csv_file():
    return pd.read_csv("my_csv_file.csv")
```

It's possible that a loadable source asset would also be observable.

The reason this is relevant to this PR: would we want the same set of required resource keys for both? If not, then maybe we should name this `observation_fn_required_resource_keys` or something?

On the other hand, it's likely that the set of required resource keys would be the same.  E.g. if your source asset is an S3 file, you likely need an S3 resource both to load it and to observe it.

@fukatani it would also be cool to update the doc string of the `predict` method a lil bit:
https://github.com/apple/coremltools/pull/1459/files#diff-03ebedd3227ecac8dfc91aa24cd7bc9a51d494d544fb4c4875588285cbe42c71R505
Maybe include a simple example that make the prediction with torch / tf tensor

Thanks a lot for the work @kazhang. I think this looks much better.

@NicolasHug could you also have a quick look just to be sure?

@vfdev-5 Does it make sense to add log calls to the `_interpolate_bilinear2d_aa` and `_interpolate_bicubic2d_aa` methods on a separate PR?

FYI @pmeier We are getting some [failures](https://app.circleci.com/pipelines/github/pytorch/vision/13463/workflows/b1e8ecdd-bff8-45bc-a880-e14b5027b5d6/jobs/1078494) on the dataset failures on the prototype.

This looks like it's just differences in pretty-printing, right? 

Because:

1) The pin is only for tests;
2) The pin doesn't drop any supported versions;
3) The pin actually brings in a number of important CVE security fixes

I'm totally fine with updating the pin.

# virtualenv activation module
# Activate with `overlay use activate.nu`
# Deactivate with `deactivate`, as usual
#
# To customize the overlay name, you can call `overlay use activate.nu as foo`,
# but then simply `deactivate` won't work because it is just an alias to hide
# the "activate" overlay. You'd need to call `overlay hide foo` manually.

export-env {
    def is-string [x] {
        ($x | describe) == 'string'
    }

    def has-env [name: string] {
        $name in (env).name
    }

    # Emulates a `test -z`, but btter as it handles e.g 'false'
    def is-env-true [name: string] {
      if (has-env $name) {
        # Try to parse 'true', '0', '1', and fail if not convertible
        let parsed = do -i { $env | get $name | into bool }
        if ($parsed | describe) == 'bool' {
          $parsed
